@node whatisasy
@section What is Asymptote?

Asymptote is a vector graphics language designed for technical graphics, inspired by MetaPost but with IEEE floating-point numerics, native three-dimensional graphics, Grayscale/RGB/CMYK colourspaces, and a C++-like syntax. Unlike MetaPost, it natively supports multiple-segment paths (and hence regions other than simply connected ones), tiling patterns, Gouraud  shading, tensor patch shading, and PostScript images.

@node whereisasy
@section How do I obtain Asymptote?

Binary releases are available for Linux, MacOS X, and Microsoft Windows platforms, in addition to full source code, from the website @uref{https://asymptote.sourceforge.io/}.  Many Linux distributions (such as RedHat and Debian) now include an Asymptote package (check your distribution's documentation for further information about this).

@node beforeasking
@section Where can I ask questions about Asymptote?

If you have a question, please try to find an answer in this FAQ, in the  extensive Asymptote documentation at @uref{https://asymptote.sourceforge.io/doc/}, or search the forum: @uref{http://sourceforge.net/forum/forum.php?forum_id=409349}.

@node whyasy
@section Why was the name Asymptote chosen?

Well, it isn't the perfect graphics package, but we do think it is getting there asymptotically...

@node whycamp
@section In the internal Asymptote source code, what does the name @code{camp} refer to?

That was our original tentative name for this project, which stood for  "C's Answer to MetaPost" (the language that inspired Asymptote).  However, we eventually decided that the name @code{Asymptote} better emphasizes the mathematical and graphical nature of this language.

