@node osx
@section Is it possible to install Asymptote on Mac OS X?

It is easy to compile Asymptote directly from the source code at @uref{http://sourceforge.net/project/showfiles.php?group_id=120000} We recommend first upgrading to the latest GNU readline library, unless you don't care about interactive readline support (in which case configure will automatically detect and disable obsolete versions of the readline library).  Marius Schamschula also maintains a binary package for various MacOS X platforms  @uref{http://www.hmug.org/pub/MacOS_X/X/Applications/Publishing/asymptote}.

@node osxbadCPU
@section Why do I get the error @code{Bad CPU type in executable} on installing Asymptote from the MAC OS binary?

This means either that you have a binary distribution for another MAC architecture, or (according to Marius Schamschula) that you may have a missing library. The simplest solution is to compile Asymptote directly from the official source: @uref{http://sourceforge.net/project/showfiles.php?group_id=120000}.

@node brokenpdftex
@section What do I do if I get the error: @code{Error: pdfetex (file pdftex.cfg): cannot open config file...texinfo.tex appears to be broken}?

Simply put @uref{https://asymptote.sourceforge.io/asymptote.pdf} in the directory @code{doc} and repeat the command @code{make all}.  Or, if you don't want to build a local copy of the documentation, simply proceed with @code{make install-asy}.

@node brokentexinfo
@section What do I do if I get the error: @code{! Undefined control sequence. l.6 @@copying}?

Either upgrade your @code{texinfo} package or follow one of the easy work arounds in @ref{brokenpdftex,,Question 2.3}.

@node latexintegration
@section Is it possible to integrate Asymptote into LaTeX?

Yes, see the example latexusage.tex. Dario Teixeira has also written a detailed guide on the topic. You can download it from @uref{http://dario.dse.nl/projects/asylatex/}.  

Philippe Ivaldi has contributed an Asymptote mode for Emacs users @uref{https://asymptote.sourceforge.io/doc/Editing-modes.html}, which includes a @code{lasy-mode} that allows one to compile and view the output of one \begin@{asy@}...\end@{asy@} section at a time.

@node pdflatex
@section Is it possible to integrate Asymptote into latex or pdflatex?

Yes, as of version 1.14, Asymptote supports latex and pdflatex (both in EPS/PDF and inline mode), as illustrated by the example @code{latexusage.tex}: 

@verbatim
pdflatex latexusage
asy latexusage
pdflatex latexusage
@end verbatim

@node tkinterdepend
@section Do I need the @code{tkinter} package to install an Asymptote rpm binary?

No, you don't need @code{tkinter} unless you want to try out the GUI @code{xasy}. Try 

@verbatim
rpm -Uvh --nodeps asymptote-x.xx-1.i386.rpm
@end verbatim

where @code{x.xx} represents the version number.

@node windir
@section What does the path @code{%USERPROFILE%\.asy\config.asy} mean?

That is the way that Microsoft Windows refers to the user profile directory.  There's nothing really to understand here, just put your configuration commands in the file @code{config.asy} in a new folder @code{%USERPROFILE%\.asy}.

@node escapechar
@section Why do I get the error "string not terminated" when I try to set @code{settings.dir="C:\asymptote\";}?

The backslash is an escape character here, so @code{\"} is interpreted as a verbatim quotation mark, leaving the string without a terminating quotation mark. Fortunately, this is the only escaped character in double-quoted strings. A final backslash isn't needed here anyway, but should you really want one somewhere, you can say: @code{settings.dir="C:\asymptote"+'\\';}.

@node winglobal
@section How do I change environment variables in Microsoft Windows, for example, in order to change the default PostScript viewer?

While it is easier to set the corresponding Asymptote configuration variable in your @code{config.asy} file, here is the procedure for changing Microsoft Windows environment variables: 

Click on the [Start] button  

* RIGHT-click on 'My Computer'  

* Choose 'Properties' from the popup menu  

* Click the 'Advanced' tab  

* Click the 'Environment Variables' button.

@node convert
@section Under Microsoft Windows XP, why do I get an error like "Invalid Parameter - 432x432"?

This means that ImageMagick wasn't properly installed and you are using the MSDOS convert program rather than the ImageMagick one. Or you may have installed ImageMagick but ran Asymptote from an existing MSDOS window.  In that case, simply open a new window and try again. If that doesn't work, check that  

@verbatim
convert --version 
@end verbatim

returns something like 

@verbatim
Version: ImageMagick 6.2.8 06/27/06 Q16 http://www.imagemagick.org
@end verbatim

@node miktex
@section Why does Asymptote freeze upon trying to draw a label with my MikTex installation under Microsoft Windows?

Likely, this means that latex and dvips are not in your default path.  Try adding the appropriate paths in your @code{config.asy} file,  for example: 

@verbatim
import settings;
latex="C:\Program Files\MiKTeX 2.7\miktex\bin\latex.exe";
dvips="C:\Program Files\MiKTeX 2.7\miktex\bin\dvips.exe";
@end verbatim

@node Questions about paths
@chapter Questions about paths

@menu
* tensionsyntax:: Question 3.1. Why do I get a syntax error message when I specify an integer value for the path tension?
* dots:: Question 3.2. Shouldn't dots always be the same size?
@end menu

@node tensionsyntax
@section Why do I get a syntax error message when I specify an integer value for the path tension?

What is happening here is that 

@verbatim
draw((0,0)..tension 2..(0,50)..(100,100));
@end verbatim

is read as  

@verbatim
draw((0,0)..tension 2. .(0,50)..(100,100));
@end verbatim

So the first . after the two is treated as a decimal point.  Just put a space after the integer tension value: 

@verbatim
draw((0,0)..tension 2 ..(0,50)..(100,100));
@end verbatim

@node dots
@section Shouldn't dots always be the same size?

From the documentation:  

"The dot command defined in the module plain draws a dot having a diameter  equal to an explicit pen linewidth or the default linewidth magnified by  dotfactor (6 by default)." 

Thus, when you use the default pen, the dot will have size 6*linewidth, but when you give a pen with an explicit width specified, you will  have a dot of size linewidth. If you want the first case to behave like the second, you may set dotfactor=1.

